<P>Page 260. <HI>Cae Dwn,</HI> or rather <HI>Cae Twn.</HI> The la&s;t, accord|ing to doctor <HI>Davies,</HI> &s;ignifies <HI>fractura,</HI> than which nothing can be more expre&s;&s;ive of the ending of this famous work, which, as I have not long &s;ince ob&s;erved, terminates in a flat cultivated country, on the farm of <HI>Cae Twn,</HI> near <HI>Tryddyn</HI> chapel, in the pa|ri&s;h of <HI>Mold.</HI> The termination is remote from any hill, or place of &s;trength: it is therefore rea&s;onable to imagine, that this mighty attempt was here &s;uddenly interrupted by &s;ome cau&s;e, of which we mu&s;t ever remain ignorant.</P>
